From: Sama Engine <engine@local>
Subject: [PATCH] renderer_vk: per-call timing for vkAcquire/Submit/Present + vkWaitForFences

Context
-------
After the MAILBOX patch (bgfx_android_mailbox_present.patch), bgfx::frameMs
on Pixel 9 still pins at the vsync floor (~16.7 ms mean, with one 9.21 ms
outlier confirming MAILBOX is engaged — that timing is impossible under
strict FIFO).  This rules out "FIFO blocking on vkAcquireNextImageKHR" as
the gate and points at compositor refresh-rate gating somewhere else in
the present pipeline, most likely vkQueuePresentKHR itself (team's
hypothesis 2 from the 2026-06-18 investigation).

To confirm, we need to know which of the four blocking Vulkan calls on
the render thread is eating the budget:
  - vkAcquireNextImageKHR (SwapChainVK::acquire)
  - vkQueueSubmit         (CommandQueueVK::kick)
  - vkWaitForFences       (CommandQueueVK::kick, after submit when _wait=true)
  - vkQueuePresentKHR     (SwapChainVK::present)

If acquire stays sub-ms and present jumps to ~14 ms, hypothesis 2 is
confirmed and the next move is upstream of bgfx — Android's
Surface.setFrameRate() / panel rate negotiation (audit #P2) or
ANativeWindow buffer transform tuning.  If waitFences is the eater, GPU
completion is the gate (worth a RenderDoc Android capture).  If submit
is the eater, command-buffer build or driver compilation is the
bottleneck (rare in steady state, possible on first frame after surface
recreation).

The patch
---------
File-static counters in the same anonymous namespace as s_presentMode
capture single-frame wall-clock for each of the four call sites.  At
the end of SwapChainVK::present — the natural end-of-frame point on the
render thread — a BX_TRACE emits all four numbers every 60 frames
(~1 s at 60 Hz).  Our BgfxLogcatCallback (engine/rendering/Renderer.cpp)
routes BX_TRACE to logcat under the SamaEngineBgfx tag, so the team can
read these directly via `adb logcat -s SamaEngineBgfx:V`.

Single-frame numbers, not accumulators — for steady-state diagnosis any
one frame is representative and the log line is easier to parse than
a 60-frame average.  The 60-frame gate keeps logcat readable without
losing the data we need.

Stays unconditional (no #ifdef) so the same APK works for desktop unit
tests and the team's Android build.  bx::getHPCounter is a few cycles;
cost is negligible against the calls being measured.

Counterpart commit on engine side documents the diagnostic;
see docs/NOTES.md "Follow-up (2026-06-18, vk per-call timing instrumentation)".
---
 bgfx/src/renderer_vk.cpp | 39 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 39 insertions(+)

diff --git a/bgfx/src/renderer_vk.cpp b/bgfx/src/renderer_vk.cpp
--- a/bgfx/src/renderer_vk.cpp
+++ b/bgfx/src/renderer_vk.cpp
@@ -155,6 +155,15 @@
 		{ VK_PRESENT_MODE_FIFO_RELAXED_KHR, true,  "VK_PRESENT_MODE_FIFO_RELAXED_KHR" },
 		{ VK_PRESENT_MODE_IMMEDIATE_KHR,    false, "VK_PRESENT_MODE_IMMEDIATE_KHR"    },
 	};
+
+	// Sama per-call vk timing diagnostic — see
+	// patches/bgfx_android_vk_call_timing.patch and docs/NOTES.md
+	// "Follow-up (2026-06-18, vk per-call timing)".
+	static int64_t  s_samaVkAcquireNs    = 0;
+	static int64_t  s_samaVkSubmitNs     = 0;
+	static int64_t  s_samaVkWaitFencesNs = 0;
+	static int64_t  s_samaVkPresentNs    = 0;
+	static uint32_t s_samaVkFrameCount   = 0;

 #define VK_IMPORT_FUNC(_optional, _func) PFN_##_func _func
 #define VK_IMPORT_INSTANCE_FUNC VK_IMPORT_FUNC
@@ -8189,6 +8198,7 @@
 			{
 				BGFX_PROFILER_SCOPE("vkAcquireNextImageKHR", kColorFrame);

+				const int64_t samaStart = bx::getHPCounter();
 				result = vkAcquireNextImageKHR(
 					  device
 					, m_swapChain
@@ -8197,6 +8207,7 @@
 					, VK_NULL_HANDLE
 					, &m_backBufferColorIdx
 					);
+				s_samaVkAcquireNs = bx::getHPCounter() - samaStart;
 			}


@@ -8266,7 +8277,26 @@
 			{
 				BGFX_PROFILER_SCOPE("vkQueuePresentHKR", kColorFrame);

+				const int64_t samaStart = bx::getHPCounter();
 				result = vkQueuePresentKHR(m_queue, &pi);
+				s_samaVkPresentNs = bx::getHPCounter() - samaStart;
+			}
+
+			// End-of-frame point on the render thread.  Dump per-call
+			// timing every 60 frames (~1 s) so the team can see which
+			// Vulkan call is eating the budget after MAILBOX engaged.
+			// Single-frame snapshot, not an accumulator — steady-state
+			// is representative and the log line is easier to read.
+			if ((++s_samaVkFrameCount % 60) == 0)
+			{
+				const double toMs = 1000.0 / double(bx::getHPFrequency());
+				BX_TRACE(
+					"Sama vk per-call ms: acquire=%.3f submit=%.3f waitFences=%.3f present=%.3f"
+					, double(s_samaVkAcquireNs)    * toMs
+					, double(s_samaVkSubmitNs)     * toMs
+					, double(s_samaVkWaitFencesNs) * toMs
+					, double(s_samaVkPresentNs)    * toMs
+					);
 			}

 			if (result != VK_SUCCESS)
@@ -8803,14 +8833,22 @@
 			{
 				BGFX_PROFILER_SCOPE("vkQueueSubmit", kColorDraw);

+				const int64_t samaStart = bx::getHPCounter();
 				VK_CHECK(vkQueueSubmit(m_queue, 1, &si, m_completedFence) );
+				s_samaVkSubmitNs = bx::getHPCounter() - samaStart;
 			}

 			if (_wait)
 			{
 				BGFX_PROFILER_SCOPE("vkWaitForFences", kColorWait);

+				const int64_t samaStart = bx::getHPCounter();
 				VK_CHECK(vkWaitForFences(device, 1, &m_completedFence, VK_TRUE, UINT64_MAX) );
+				s_samaVkWaitFencesNs = bx::getHPCounter() - samaStart;
+			}
+			else
+			{
+				s_samaVkWaitFencesNs = 0;
 			}

 			m_activeCommandBuffer = VK_NULL_HANDLE;
